{
  "texts": [
    "(2) We say that the prescribed Jacobian equation has linearised Lipschitz non-regularity if there exists some ρ ∈ L ∞ (Q) for which there does not exists a Lipschitz solution (f i, π i) to (1.3).",
    "(3) We say that the prescribed Jacobian equation has strong Lipschitz non-regularity if a sequence of L 1 (Q) functions u n, n ∈ N can be found satisfying the two following inequalities simultaneously:(i) for each n ∈ N, ∥u n ∥ L 1 (Q) ≥ 1 (ii) for each n ∈ N, sup    Q u n f det Dπ dL d: max{Lip(f), ∥f ∥ ∞ } d j=1 Lip(π j) ≤ 1    ≤ 1 n.It is clear that linearised Lipschitz non-regularity implies weak Lipschitz non-regularity.",
    "To see that strong Lipschitz non-regularity implies linearised Lipschitz non-regularity we essentially \"repeat\" the proof of the open mapping theorem in a different setting.",
    "LetK = {f det Dπ: max{Lip(f), ∥f ∥ ∞ } d j=1 Lip(π j) ≤ 1} ⊂ L ∞ (Q).If the prescribed Jacobian equation does not have linearised Lipschitz non-regularity, then in particularn∈N {nρ: ρ ∈ conv K} = L ∞ (Q).Thus, an application of the Baire category theorem shows that for at least one n ∈ N, the set {nρ: ρ ∈ conv K} has non-empty interior.",
    "By the homogeneity of the determinant, we may freely rescale the set and see that in fact the set conv K contains an open neighbourhood of 0."
  ]
}